# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avalites
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] The **1st century BC**, also known as the **last century BC** and the **last century BCE**, started on the first day of 100 BC and ended on the last day of 1 BC.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] The AD/BC notation does not use a year zero; however, astronomical year numbering does use a zero, as well as a minus sign, so "2 BC" is equal to "year –1".
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] In the course of the century, all the remaining independent lands surrounding the Mediterranean Sea were steadily brought under Roman control, being ruled either directly under governors or through puppet kings appointed by Rome.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] The Roman state itself was plunged into civil war several times, finally resulting in the marginalization of its 500-year-old Roman Republic, and the embodiment of total state power in a single man—the Roman emperor.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] The internal turbulence that plagued Rome at this time can be seen as the death throes of the Roman Republic, as it finally gave way to the autocratic ambitions of powerful men like Sulla, Julius Caesar, Mark Antony and Octavian.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] Octavian's ascension to total power as the emperor Augustus is considered to mark the point in history where the Roman Republic ends and the Roman Empire begins.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] Some scholars refer to this event as the Roman Revolution.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] In the eastern mainland, the Han dynasty began to decline and the court of China was in chaos in the latter half of this century.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] Trapped in a difficult situation, the Xiongnu had to begin emigration to the west or attach themselves to the Han.
[src:avalites/1st-century-bc] See: List of sovereign states in the 1st century BC.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **1st century** was the century spanning AD 1 (represented by the Roman numeral I) through AD 100 (C) according to the Julian calendar.
[src:avalites/1st-century] It is often written as the **1st century AD** or **1st century CE** to distinguish it from the 1st century BC (or BCE) which preceded it.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The 1st century is considered part of the Classical era, epoch, or historical period.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Roman Empire, Han China and Parthia were the most powerful and hegemonic states.
[src:avalites/1st-century] During this century, the Roman Empire (ruled by the Julio-Claudian and Flavian dynasties) continued to be in a period of relative stability known as Pax Romana, withstanding a financial crisis in 33 and a civil war in 69.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Europe, Rome expanded into Britain and fought wars in Germania and Dacia.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Africa, Rome was challenged by Tacfarinas, who led his own Musulamii tribe and a loose and changing coalition of other Berber tribes before being defeated in 24.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In West Asia, Rome defeated a Jewish rebellion (66–73) and fought a war with Parthia from 58 to 63, though the latter conflict was inconclusive.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In East Asia, the Chinese Western Han dynasty was overthrown and replaced by the Xin dynasty in 9, which in turn faced its own rebel movements (namely the Red Eyebrows and Lulin), and was replaced by the Eastern Han dynasty in 25.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Eastern Han dynasty then faced and quelled a rebellion by the Trưng sisters (40–43).
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 58, the Eastern Han dynasty entered a golden age with the Rule of Ming and Zhang, who were generally regarded as able administrators who cared about the common welfare of the people and who promoted officials with integrity.
[src:avalites/1st-century] On its northern frontier, the Chinese dynasties waged intermittent war with the Xiongnu before emerging victorious in 91.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The states of Funan and Xianbei were also established in this century.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The century saw the origination of Christianity from Palestine.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the early 30s, Roman governor Pontius Pilate sentenced Jesus to crucifixion; his suffering and redemptive death by crucifixion would become central aspects of Christian theology concerning the doctrines of salvation and atonement.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Anti-Jewish riots broke out in Alexandria in 38.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 64, the Great Fire of Rome destroyed two-thirds of the city, precipitating the empire's first persecution of Christians, who were blamed for the disaster.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Later in 70, the siege and subsequent sack of Jerusalem and the Second Temple during the First Jewish–Roman War marked a major turning point in Jewish history.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The loss of mother-city and temple necessitated a reshaping of Jewish culture to ensure its survival.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Judaism's Temple-based sects, including the priesthood and the Sadducees, diminished in importance.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Second Temple Judaism came to an end, while a new form of Judaism that became known as Rabbinic Judaism developed out of the Pharisaic school.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Furthermore, the White Horse Temple, the first Buddhist temple in China, was traditionally constructed in 68, though it is not recorded in contemporary sources before 289.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Several natural disasters took place in this century.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 17, an earthquake struck the region of Lydia in the Roman province of Asia in Asia Minor (now part of Turkey), causing the destruction of at least 12 cities, with Sardis being most affected.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Around 44 to 48, a famine took place in Judea, precipitating assistance by Helena of Adiabene and her son, Izates II.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 62, an earthquake of an estimated magnitude of between 5 and 6 and a maximum intensity of IX or X on the Mercalli scale struck the towns of Pompeii and Herculaneum, severely damaging them; damage to some buildings in Naples and Nuceria was also reported.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 79, Mount Vesuvius violently spewed forth a deadly cloud of super-heated tephra and gases to a height of 33 km (21 mi), ejecting molten rock, pulverized pumice and hot ash.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The event destroyed several towns and minor settlements in the area, at the time part of the Roman Empire, with Pompeii and Herculaneum being the most famous examples.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The total population of both cities was over twenty thousand.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The remains of over 1,500 people have been found at Pompeii and Herculaneum so far, although the total death toll from the eruption remains unknown.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Death toll estimates range from 13,000 to 16,000.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **0s** began on January 1, AD 1 and ended on December 31, AD 9, covering the first nine years of the Common Era.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Europe, the 0s saw the continuation of conflict between the Roman Empire and Germanic tribes in the Early Imperial campaigns in Germania.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Vinicius, Tiberius and Varus led Roman forces in multiple punitive campaigns, before sustaining a major defeat at the hands of Arminius in the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Concurrently, the Roman Empire fought the Bellum Batonianum against a rebelling alliance of native peoples led by Bato the Daesitiate in Illyricum, which was suppressed in AD 9.
[src:avalites/1st-century] A conflict also took place in Korea, where Daeso, King of Dongbuyeo invaded Goguryeo with a 50,000-man army in AD 6.
[src:avalites/1st-century] He was forced to retreat when heavy snow began to fall, stopping the conflict until the next decade.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, the last ruler of the Chinese Western Han dynasty (Ruzi Ying) was deposed, allowing Wang Mang to establish the Xin dynasty.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Nicolaus of Damascus wrote the 15-volume *History of the World*.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Estimates for the world population by AD 1 range from 170 to 300 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] A census was concluded in China in AD 2: final numbers showed a population of nearly 60 million (59,594,978 people in slightly more than 12 million households).
[src:avalites/1st-century] The census is one of the most accurate surveys in Chinese history.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **10s** decade ran from January 1, AD 10, to December 31, AD 19.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Europe, the decade saw the end of the Early Imperial campaigns in Germania when Roman forces led by Germanicus defeated Germanic tribes in the Battle of Idistaviso in AD 16.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the subsequent year, a war broke out between Maroboduus and Arminius.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Africa, Tacfarinas led his own Musulamii tribe and a loose and changing coalition of other Berber tribes in a war against the Romans in North Africa during the rule of the emperor Tiberius (AD 14–37).
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Armenian Artaxiad dynasty was overthrown by the Romans.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, the Red Eyebrows Rebellion erupted against Wang Mang, emperor of the Xin dynasty.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Korea, Daeso, the ruler of the kingdom of Dongbuyeo, led his armies into Goguryeo once again.
[src:avalites/1st-century] This time, Muhyul, a prince of Goguryeo, led the armies of Goguryeo in a well-planned ambush and slaughtered all of Daeso's army.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Only he and a few of his men escaped home.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Literary works from the 10s include works from the ancient Roman poet Ovid, *Tristia* and *Epistulae ex Ponto,* while Nicolaus of Damascus wrote a biography of Emperor Augustus (*Bios Kaisaros*).
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the Roman Empire, an edict was issued effecting an empire-wide ban on divinatory practices especially astrology.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The edict requires any consultation between a customer and a practitioner to be conducted with at least one third party witness present and bans inquiry into anyone's death.
[src:avalites/1st-century] A large earthquake caused the destruction of at least twelve cities in the region of Lydia in the Roman province of Asia in Asia Minor.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, a major flooding took place in the Yellow River in AD 11, which is credited with helping bring about the fall of the Xin dynasty in the next decade.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 10 as 241 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **20s** decade ran from January 1, AD 20, to December 31, AD 29.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Europe, the 20s saw revolts by the Aedui, Thracian tribesmen, and the Frisians against the Roman Empire.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In North Africa, Tacfarinas, a Numidian Berber deserter, led the Musulamii tribe and a loose and changing coalition of other Berber tribes in revolt, before being defeated in AD 24.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, the Xin dynasty collapsed and the Eastern Han dynasty was established.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Korea, Daemusin of Goguryeo annexed Dongbuyeo and killed its king Daeso.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In science, the 20s saw the manufacture of pens and metal writing tools in Rome.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Major disasters of this decade include a fire in Rome, and the collapse of a poorly built amphitheatre in Fidenae, which killed 20,000 of the 50,000 spectators.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 27, Christianity originates from Judaea as a Jewish Christian sect of the Second Temple Judaism.
[src:avalites/1st-century] *Geographica*, an encyclopedia of geographical knowledge created by Strabo, was finished no later than AD 23.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 20 as 246 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **30s** decade ran from January 1, AD 30, to December 31, AD 39.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Jesus was crucified early in the decade, an event generally accepted by historians; the understanding of his suffering and death as redemptive developed later as a central element of Christian teachings on salvation and atonement.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Peter the Apostle founded the Church of Antioch.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Anti-Jewish riots broke out in Alexandria.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Asia, the Western Satraps and Kushan Empire emerged.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In Europe, the 30s saw a Dacian revolt against the Sarmatian tribe of Iazyges, who had enslaved them, and a Samaritan uprising.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In west Asia, Artabanus II of Parthia fought a war with Rome over Armenia.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Han dynasty saw the outbreak of the Rebellion of Gongsun Shu.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Roman emperor Tiberius died in AD 37, being succeeded by Caligula.
[src:avalites/1st-century] An earthquake that shook Antioch in AD 37 caused the emperor Caligula to send two senators to report on the condition of the city.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, an epidemic broke out in K'aui-chi, causing many deaths, and Imperial official Ch'ung-li I (Zhongli Yi) provided medicine that saved many lives.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Valerius Maximus wrote *Factorum ac dictorum memorabilium libri IX*: It is a collection of approximately a thousand short stories that Valerius wrote during the reign of Tiberius (42 BC – AD 37).
[src:avalites/1st-century] Other literary works from the 30s include a popular collection of fables written by Phaedrus, a symbolic interpretation of the Old Testament *(Allegory)* written by Philo, and a general history of the countries known in Antiquity written by Velleius Paterculus.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 30 as 247 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **40s** decade ran from January 1, AD 40, to December 31, AD 49.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Claudius became Roman Emperor in 41, following the assassination of Caligula.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 43, he sent Aulus Plautius with four legions to Britain (*Britannia*), initiating the decades-long Roman conquest of Britain.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, The Trưng sisters' rebellion took place in the south of Han China between 40 AD and 43 AD: In 40 AD, the Vietnamese leader Trưng Trắc and her sister Trưng Nhị rebelled against Chinese authorities in Jiaozhi (in what is now northern Vietnam).
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 42 AD, Han China dispatched General Ma Yuan to lead an army to strike down the Yue rebellion of the Trưng sisters.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 43 AD, the Han army fully suppressed the uprising and regained complete control.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Christianity came to Egypt as the Church of Alexandria was founded with Mark the Evangelist as the first Patriarch.
[src:avalites/1st-century] James the Great died in 44: One of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus, he was the first to be martyred according to the New Testament.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Claudius expelled the Jews from Rome between 41 and 53: Silvia Cappelletti describes Claudius's motivation as the need to control the population of Rome and prevent political meetings.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Between 44 and 48, a famine took place in Judea.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Josephus relates that Helena of Adiabene "went down to the city Jerusalem, her son conducting her on her journey a great way.
[src:avalites/1st-century] And as soon as they were come back, and had brought those provisions, which was done very quickly, she distributed food to those that were in want of it, and left a most excellent memorial behind her of this benefaction, which she bestowed on our whole nation.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Literary works of this decade include the *Histories of Alexander the Great* (written by Quintus Curtius Rufus), and essays by Seneca (including *De Ira*, *Ad Marciam, De consolatione*, *De Brevitate Vitæ*, *De Consolatione ad Polybium*, and *Ad Helviam matrem, De consolatione*).
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 40 as 247 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **50s** decade ran from January 1, 50, to December 31, 59.
[src:avalites/1st-century] It was the sixth decade in the Anno Domini/Common Era, if the nine-year period from 1 AD to 9 AD is considered as a "decade".
[src:avalites/1st-century] The early years of the decade saw Roman and Parthian intervention in the Iberian–Armenian War, a conflict which led Tiridates I to become King of Armenia with Parthian support.
[src:avalites/1st-century] This was unacceptable to Rome, and the ensuing tensions culminated in the Roman–Parthian War of 58–63.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Concurrently, the Roman conquest of Britain continued, with Caratacus being defeated in 50 and tribes of modern Wales being subdued in 58 to 59.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 50, the Southern Xiongnu submitted to the Chinese Han dynasty.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Later in 57, the ascension of Emperor Ming heralded the beginning of a golden age.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Council of Jerusalem was held early in the decade: The council decided that Gentile converts to Christianity were not obligated to keep most of the fasts, and other specific rituals, including the rules concerning circumcision of males.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Council did, however, retain the prohibitions on eating blood, meat containing blood, and meat of animals that were strangled, and on fornication and idolatry.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Literary works of this decade include *De Vita Beata* (which explains that the pursuit of happiness is the pursuit of reason) and *De Clementia* (an instructional contrast between the good ruler and a tyrant), both of which were written by Seneca the Younger.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 50 as 248 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **60s** decade ran from January 1, AD 60, to December 31, AD 69.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the Roman Empire, the early part of the decade saw the beginning of the Boudican Revolt in Britannia, where several tribes (chiefly the Iceni), led by Boudica, rebelled against the Roman occupation.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The revolt led to the sacking of several Roman cities, but was ultimately quelled by governor Gaius Suetonius Paulinus.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 63, the Roman–Parthian War came to an end with the Treaty of Rhandeia.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 66, the First Jewish-Roman War began, as Jewish rebels fought against Roman rule.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Near the end of the decade in 69, the Year of the Four Emperors saw a period of civil war and political instability in the Roman Empire, as four different men (Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and Vespasian) claimed the title of Emperor within the span of a year.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Ultimately, the year ended with the ascension of Vespasian to the throne and the beginning of the Flavian Dynasty.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In East Asia, the state of Funan was established, while China continued its golden age.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 62, an earthquake of an estimated magnitude of between 5 and 6 and a maximum intensity of IX or X on the Mercalli scale struck the towns of Pompeii and Herculaneum, severely damaging them.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The towns of Pompeii and Herculaneum both suffered major damage, with damage to some buildings also reported from Naples and Nuceria.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Seneca reported the death of a flock of 600 sheep that he attributed to the effects of poisonous gases.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Later, in 64, the Great Fire of Rome began in the merchant shops around Rome's chariot stadium, Circus Maximus.
[src:avalites/1st-century] After six days, the fire was brought under control, but before the damage could be assessed, the fire reignited and burned for another three days.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the aftermath of the fire, two-thirds of Rome had been destroyed.
[src:avalites/1st-century] According to Tacitus and later Christian tradition, Emperor Nero blamed the devastation on the Christian community in the city, initiating the empire's first persecution against the Christians.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the Roman Empire, Christianity continued to spread, despite a campaign of persecution being initiated under Emperor Nero in 64.
[src:avalites/1st-century] According to tradition, the apostles Peter and Paul were both martyred during this period: Traditionally, Roman authorities allegedly sentenced Peter to death by crucifixion at Vatican Hill.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In accordance with the apocryphal Acts of Peter, he was crucified head down.
[src:avalites/1st-century] As for Paul, the Second Epistle to Timothy states that he was arrested in Troad and brought back to Rome, where he was imprisoned and put on trial before being executed.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The White Horse Temple, the first Buddhist temple in China, was traditionally constructed in 68, though it is not recorded in contemporary sources before 289.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 62 or 64, the Baths of Nero were constructed.
[src:avalites/1st-century] It stood between the Pantheon and the Stadium of Domitian and were listed among the most notable buildings in the city by Roman authors and became a much-frequented venue.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In his final years, Seneca the Younger wrote *De Providentia* (discussing the problem of evil), *De Beneficiis* (discussing the award and reception of gifts and favours within society), and compiled a collection of 124 written near the end of his life.
[src:avalites/1st-century] After Seneca's death in 65, a play named *Octavia* was written: the Roman tragedy focuses on three days in the year 62 during which Nero divorced and exiled his wife Claudia Octavia and married another (Poppaea Sabina).
[src:avalites/1st-century] The play also deals with the irascibility of Nero and his inability to take heed of the philosopher Seneca's advice to rein in his passions.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The *Pharsalia*, a poem detailing Caesar's civil war (49–45 BC), was also written during this decade.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 60 as 249 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **70s** was a decade that ran from January 1, AD 70, to December 31, AD 79.
[src:avalites/1st-century] As the decade began, the First Jewish–Roman War continued: In AD 70, the Romans besieged and sacked Jerusalem and destroyed the Second Temple.
[src:avalites/1st-century] After this major victory, the Romans continued to clear pockets of Jewish resistance, with the final stronghold taken being Masada (73).
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Flavian dynasty, which included emperors Vespasian and Titus, ruled the empire during this decade.
[src:avalites/1st-century] During their reign, the Romans faced military challenges from various sources, including clashes with British and Germanic tribes.
[src:avalites/1st-century] However, the Romans were largely successful in defeating these tribes, expanding their territories and consolidating their power.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Following the death of Vologases I in 78, Parthia saw internal conflict as Vologases II and Pacorus II competed for the throne.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, the Han–Xiongnu War was re-invigorated, with the Han defeating the Northern Xiongnu in the Battle of Yiwulu (73).
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 75, Emperor Ming of Han died, being succeeded by Emperor Zhang: the reign of these two emperors is considered to have been a golden age.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The destruction of Jerusalem and the Second Temple during the First Jewish–Roman War marked a major turning point in Jewish history.
[src:avalites/1st-century] A new form of Judaism that became known as Rabbinic Judaism developed out of Pharisaic school and, centuries later, eventually became the mainstream form of the religion.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Many followers of Jesus of Nazareth also survived the city's destruction.
[src:avalites/1st-century] They spread his teachings across the Roman Empire, giving rise to the new religion of Christianity.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the autumn of 79, Mount Vesuvius violently spewed forth a deadly cloud of super-heated tephra and gases to a height of 33 km (21 mi), ejecting molten rock, pulverized pumice and hot ash.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The event destroyed several towns and minor settlements in the area, at the time part of the Roman Empire.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Pompeii and Herculaneum, obliterated and buried underneath massive pyroclastic surges and ashfall deposits, are the most famous examples.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The total population of both cities was over 20,000.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The period also saw significant architectural and engineering accomplishments, such as the construction of the Colosseum in Rome.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 75, Vespasian erected a colossal statue of Apollo, begun under Nero, and he dedicated a stage of the theatre of Marcellus.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Valerius Flaccus wrote the *Argonautica*, an epic poem.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Pliny the Elder composed the 10-volume *Natural History*, covering topics including astronomy, mathematics, geography, ethnography, anthropology, human physiology, zoology, botany, agriculture, horticulture, pharmacology, mining, mineralogy, sculpture, art, and precious stones.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 70 to have been 250 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **80s** was a decade that ran from January 1, AD 80, to December 31, AD 89.
[src:avalites/1st-century] As the decade began, the Parthian Empire was in a phase of division until Pacorus II managed to consolidate his rule, eliminating the two rival contenders for his throne: Vologases II in AD 80 and Artabanus III in AD 81.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Domitian became Roman emperor in AD 81: The military campaigns undertaken during his reign were generally defensive in nature, as the Emperor rejected the idea of expansionist warfare.
[src:avalites/1st-century] His most significant military contribution was the development of the Limes Germanicus, which encompassed a vast network of roads, forts and watchtowers constructed along the Rhine river to defend the Empire.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Nevertheless, several important wars were fought in Gaul, against the Chatti, and across the Danube frontier against the Suebi, the Sarmatians, and the Dacians (see Domitian's Dacian War).
[src:avalites/1st-century] In northern Britain, the Romans defeated local tribes in the Battle of Mons Graupius (AD 83).
[src:avalites/1st-century] In China, the Han–Xiongnu War continued, with the Battle of the Altai Mountains (AD 89) bringing the Northern Xiongnu to the brink of collapse.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The death of Emperor Zhang of Han ended a golden age.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In spring of AD 80, a fire broke out in Rome and burned large parts of the city for three days and three nights.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Emperor Titus personally compensated for the damaged regions.
[src:avalites/1st-century] According to Suetonius, a plague also broke out during the fire.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The nature of the disease, however, and the death toll are unknown.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Manning (2008) tentatively estimates the world population in AD 80 to have been 250 million.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The **90s** was a decade that ran from January 1, AD 90, to December 31, AD 99.
[src:avalites/1st-century] As the decade began, the Han–Xiongnu War was approaching its end, with the Xiongnu having been on the verge of collapse since the Battle of the Altai Mountains (89) the prior decade.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In 90, Dou Xian dispatched General Geng Kui and Shizi of the Southern Xiongnu with 8000 light cavalry to attack the Northern Chanyu, encamped at Heyun (河雲).
[src:avalites/1st-century] There, the Han killed 8000 men and captured several thousands.
[src:avalites/1st-century] By 91, the last remnants of the Northern Xiongnu had migrated west towards the Ili River valley, ending the war.
[src:avalites/1st-century] After the downfall of the Xiongnu, the Xianbei replaced them with a loose confederacy from 93.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Roman Empire did not see any significant military action this decade, excepting clashes along the Danube in 92.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Economically, the empire saw reforms by Nerva after the death of Domitian in 96, including but not limited to a string of economic reforms intended to alleviate the burden of taxation from the most needy Romans.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Before long, Nerva's expenses strained the economy of Rome and, although perhaps not ruinous to the extent once suggested by Syme, necessitated the formation of a special commission of economy to drastically reduce expenditures.
[src:avalites/1st-century] According to some historians, Jews and Christians were heavily persecuted toward the end of Domitian's reign (89-96).
[src:avalites/1st-century] The Book of Revelation, which mentions at least one instance of martyrdom (Rev 2:13; cf.
[src:avalites/1st-century] 6:9), is thought by many scholars to have been written during Domitian's reign.
[src:avalites/1st-century] According to Barnes, "Melito, Tertullian, and Bruttius stated that Domitian persecuted the Christians.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Melito and Bruttius vouchsafe no details, Tertullian only that Domitian soon changed his mind and recalled those whom he had exiled".
[src:avalites/1st-century] A minority of the historians have maintained that there was little or no anti-Christian activity during Domitian's time.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The lack of consensus by historians about the extent of persecution during the reign of Domitian derives from the fact that while accounts of persecution exist, these accounts are cursory or their reliability is debated.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In AD 92, the Flavian Palace was completed.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In AD 97, the Forum of Nerva was completed.
[src:avalites/1st-century] Josephus wrote *Antiquities of the Jews* (covering the history of the Jewish people), *Against Apion* (a defense of Judaism as a classical religion and philosophy against criticism by Apion), and *The Life of Flavius Josephus* (an autobiographical text where Josephus details his own life).
[src:avalites/1st-century] Tacitus wrote *Germania* (a historical and ethnographic work on the Germanic peoples outside the Roman Empire) and *Agricola* (which recounts the life of his father-in-law Gnaeus Julius Agricola, an eminent Roman general and governor of Britain).
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the Roman Empire, it was sometimes referred to as **year 853 *ab urbe condita***, i.e., 853 years since the founding of Rome in 753 B.C.
[src:avalites/1st-century] The denomination AD 100 for this year has been used since the Early Middle Ages, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
[src:avalites/1st-century] This year saw Pacores, the last king of the Indo-Parthian kingdom, ascend to the throne.
[src:avalites/1st-century] In the Americas, the Moche culture developed around this time, and Teotihuacan, a major city at the centre of modern-day Mexico, reached a population of around 60,000–80,000.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] The **2nd century** is the period from AD 101 (represented by the Roman numerals CI) through AD 200 (CC) in accordance with the Julian calendar.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] It is considered part of the Classical era, epoch, or historical period.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] Early in the century, the Roman Empire attained its greatest expansion under the emperor Trajan, but after his death became primarily defensive for the rest of its history.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] Much prosperity took place throughout the empire at this time, ruled as it was by the "Five Good Emperors", a succession of well-received and able rulers.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] This period also saw the removal of the Jews from Jerusalem during the reign of Hadrian after Bar Kokhba's revolt.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] The last quarter of the century saw the end of the period of peace and prosperity known as the Pax Romana at the death of the emperor Marcus Aurelius, last of the "Five Good Emperors", and the ascension of Commodus.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] After Commodus was murdered in 192, a turbulent period known as the Year of the Five Emperors ensued.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] After the quick successive removals of Pertinax and Didius Julianus from power, this period had the general-turned-emperor Septimius Severus, who was the founder of the Severan dynasty, pitted against rival claimants in the form of Pescennius Niger.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] Severus' forces defeated the rival claimants at the Battle of Issus in 194, and Clodius Albinus, whom he defeated at the Battle of Lugdunum in 197, granting Severus sole authority over the empire.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] Although the Han dynasty of China was firmly cemented into power and extended its imperial influence into Central Asia during the first half of the century, by the second half there was widespread corruption and open rebellion.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] Warlords and government officials quickly took against him in a campaign that, while failing to put him down, compelled Dong Zhuo to shift the seat of imperial power further west to Chang'an.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] As Dong Zhuo was killed in 192, the chaos in the wake of the collapse of centralized authority only continued, with various warlords attempting to vie for supremacy in order to establish or hold onto their authority within the decaying empire.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] Meanwhile, Dong Zhuo's former followers Li Jue and Guo Si were left to squabble amongst themselves, while Emperor Xian himself fled and returned to the ravaged city of Luoyang.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] In 196, he was given refuge by the warlord Cao Cao, who relocated him to the new capital city of Xu, from where he could control the emperor.
[src:avalites/2nd-century] Cao Cao would further exert his authority by defeating the powerful warlord Yuan Shao at the decisive Battle of Guandu in 200.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] The **3rd century** was the period from AD 201 (represented by the Roman numerals CCI) to AD 300 (CCC) in accordance with the Julian calendar.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] This crisis would also mark the beginning of Late Antiquity.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] While in North Africa, Roman rule continued with growing Christian influence, particularly in the region of Carthage.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] In Persia, the Parthian Empire was succeeded by the Sassanid Empire in 224 after Ardashir I defeated and killed Artabanus V during the Battle of Hormozdgan.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] The Sassanids then went on to subjugate many of the western portions of the declining Kushan Empire.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] In Africa the most significant event was the rise of the Aksumite Empire in what is now Ethiopia, which experienced significant military expansion and became a major trading hub in northeast Africa.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] In other parts of the world, Korea was ruled by the Three Kingdoms of Korea, Japan entered the Kofun period and the Southeast Asian mainland was mostly dominated by Funan, the first kingdom of the Khmer people.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] In India, the Gupta Empire was on the rise towards the end of the century.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] In Pre-Columbian America, the Adena culture of the Ohio River valley declined in favor of the Hopewell culture.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] The Maya civilization entered its Classic Era.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] After the death of Commodus in the late previous century the Roman Empire was plunged into a civil war.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] When the dust settled, Septimius Severus emerged as emperor, establishing the Severan dynasty.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] Unlike previous emperors, he openly used the army to back his authority, and paid them well to do so.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] The regime he created is known as the Military Monarchy as a result.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] The majority of these men were assassinated, or killed in battle, and the empire almost collapsed under the weight of the political upheaval, as well as the growing Persian threat in the east.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] Under its new Sassanid rulers, Persia had grown into a rival superpower, and the Romans would have to make drastic reforms in order to better prepare their state for a confrontation.
[src:avalites/3rd-century] These reforms were finally realized late in the century under the reign of Diocletian, one of them being to divide the empire into an eastern and western half, and have a separate ruler for each.
[src:avalites/6th-century] The **6th century** is the period from 501 through 600 in line with the Julian calendar.
[src:avalites/6th-century] In the West, the century marks the end of Classical Antiquity and the beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:avalites/6th-century] The collapse of the Western Roman Empire late in the previous century left Europe fractured into many small Germanic kingdoms competing fiercely for land and wealth.
[src:avalites/6th-century] From the upheaval the Franks rose to prominence and carved out a sizeable domain covering much of modern France and Germany.
[src:avalites/6th-century] Meanwhile, the surviving Eastern Roman Empire began to expand under Emperor Justinian, who recaptured North Africa from the Vandals and attempted fully to recover Italy as well, in the hope of reinstating Roman control over the lands once ruled by the Western Roman Empire.
[src:avalites/6th-century] Owing in part to the collapse of the Roman Empire along with its literature and civilization, the sixth century is generally considered to be the least known about in the Dark Ages.
[src:avalites/6th-century] In its second golden age, the Sassanid Empire reached the peak of its power under Khosrau I in the 6th century.
[src:avalites/6th-century] The classical Gupta Empire of Northern India, largely overrun by the Huna, ended in the mid-6th century.
[src:avalites/6th-century] In Japan, the Kofun period gave way to the Asuka period.
[src:avalites/6th-century] After being divided for more than 150 years among the Northern and Southern dynasties, China was reunited under the Sui dynasty toward the end of the 6th century.
[src:avalites/6th-century] The Three Kingdoms of Korea persisted throughout the century.
[src:avalites/6th-century] The Göktürks became a major power in Central Asia after defeating the Rouran.
[src:avalites/6th-century] In the Americas, Teotihuacan began to decline in the 6th century after having reached its zenith between AD 150 and 450.
[src:avalites/6th-century] Classic period of the Maya civilization in Central America.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] Hailing from the Ahmed Abdalla branch of the Habr Awal Saad Musa, Abdulrahman was crowned Sultan after his father Sultan Dirriye's death.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] Sultan Abdulrahman was very much like his father filling the role of a peacemaker, however he was much more active in protectorate affairs.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] During his reign the Isamusa would split and crown their own Sultan although continuing to recognize Abdulrahman as their ultimate authority of the Habr Awal.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] When the Eidagale attempted to raid the Isamusa, a son of the Habr Yunis Sultan joined the raid and when the raiders were pursued he was killed.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] The Sultan of the Habr Yunis approached Abdulrahman to resolve the dispute and wanted him to compel the Isamusa to pay *mag* for the Sultan's son.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] According to traditional Somali *xeer* restitution is not paid when one is killed in self defense.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] So the Isamusa refused and banged their shields in disproval of Abdulrahman's judgement.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] Cismaan Haariyey a poet stood and recited the following *geeraar* reaffirming his respect but disagreeing with Sultan Abdulrahman.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] After this the Issa Musa would leave and go on to crown their first Sultan, Sultan Koshin in 1949 marking their independence from their larger Saad Musa brethren.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] In the year 1955, Sultan Abdulrahman Deria was a member of a 4 delegation team of politicians and Sultans to London, United Kingdom.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] Their goal was to petition and pressure the British Government in returning lost treaty territory known as the 'Haud Reserve Area' ceded to Ethiopian Empire during the Anglo Ethiopian treaty of 1954.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] Following the end of British Somaliland and subsequent unification in 1960.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] Sultan Abdulrahman would later be arrested and targeted by Somali authorities in 1965 alongside other leading Habr Awal figures after being accused of supporting Ethiopian Habr Awals in clan clashes.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] The SNA was deployed across the border and against sections of the clan, before the Ethiopian Army intervened and repulsed them.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] There was mass movement by the Habr Awal against this motion and in defense of their Sultan who was eventually released.
[src:avalites/abdulrahman-deria] Abdulrahman would later die in his early 60s and was succeeded by his son Sultan Cabdillahi.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Abraham Ortelius was born on either 4 April or 14 April 1527 in the city of Antwerp, which was then in the Spanish Netherlands.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] The Ortels or Wortels (latinized as Orthellius and Ortelius) family was originally from Augsburg, a Free imperial city of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Abraham's grandfather, Willem Ortels, was a pharmacist.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] He had moved in 1460 to Antwerp where he married Mathilde 's Jagers, alias Reynaerts.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] From his second marriage with Maria Antheard a son called Willem was born.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] The family lived in the Kipdorp street in Antwerp and was fairly well off.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Leonard Ortelius married Anna Herwayers and they had three children, Abraham, Anna who would stay on her brother's side and Elisabeth who married a trader named Jacob Cool Sr., whose son Jacob Cool Jr.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] (known as Ortelianus) would be the principal heir of Abraham Ortelius.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] He spoke Greek and Latin, and worked with his brother-in-law Jacob van Meteren on the translation of Miles Coverdale's English Bible.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1535, they were both prosecuted for possessing suspicious books.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Searches turned up nothing and the case was subsequently dismissed.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Leonard Ortelius was a successful antique dealer.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Following the death of his father, Abraham Ortelius's uncle Jacobus van Meteren returned from exile in England to take care of him.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Abraham remained close to his cousin Emanuel van Meteren, who would later move to London.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1575 Abraham was appointed geographer to the king of Spain, Philip II, on the recommendation of Arias Montanus, who vouched for his orthodoxy.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Beginning as a map-engraver, in 1547 he entered the Antwerp Guild of Saint Luke as an illuminator of maps.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] He supplemented his income trading in books, prints, and maps, and his journeys included annual visits to the Frankfurt book and print fair, where he met Gerardus Mercator in 1554.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1560, however, when travelling with Mercator to Trier, Lorraine, and Poitiers, he seems to have been attracted, largely by Mercator's influence, towards the career of a scientific geographer.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1564, he published his first map, “Nova Totius Terrarum Orbis Iuxta Neo Terricorum Traditiones Descripto”, an eight-leaved wall map of the world, on which he identified the *Regio Patalis* with *Locach* as a northward extension of the *Terra Australis*, reaching as far as New Guinea.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] (the only extant copy is now at Basel University Library).
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] He also published a two-sheet map of Egypt in 1565, a plan of the Brittenburg castle on the coast of the Netherlands in 1568, an eight-sheet map of Asia in 1567, and a six-sheet map of Spain before the appearance of his atlas.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In England Ortelius's contacts included William Camden, Richard Hakluyt, Thomas Penny, Puritan controversialist William Charke, and Humphrey Llwyd, who would contribute the map of England and Wales to Ortelius's 1573 edition of the *Theatrum*.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1596, he received a presentation from Antwerp, similar to that afterwards bestowed on Peter Paul Rubens.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] His death on 28 June 1598 and his burial in the church of St.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Michael's Abbey, Antwerp, were marked by public mourning.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] The inscription on his tombstone reads: *Quietis cultor sine lite, uxore, prole* ("served quietly, without accusation, wife, and offspring").
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] On 20 May 1570, Gilles Coppens de Diest at Antwerp issued Ortelius's *Theatrum Orbis Terrarum*, the "first modern atlas" (of 53 maps).
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Three Latin editions of this (besides a Dutch, a French, and a German edition) appeared before the end of 1572; twenty-five editions came out before Ortelius's death in 1598; and several others were published subsequently, for the atlas continued to be in demand until about 1612.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Most of the maps were admittedly reproductions (a list of 87 authors is given in the first *Theatrum* by Ortelius himself, growing to 183 names in the 1601 Latin edition), and many discrepancies of delineation or nomenclature occur.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1573, Ortelius published seventeen supplementary maps under the title *Additamentum Theatri Orbis Terrarum*.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Four more Additamenta were to follow, the last one appearing in 1597.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1579, Ortelius brought out his *Nomenclator Ptolemaicus* and started his *Parergon* (a series of maps illustrating ancient history, sacred and secular).
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] He also published *Itinerarium per nonnullas Galliae Belgicae partes* (at the Plantin press in 1584, and reprinted in 1630, 1661 in Hegenitius, Itin.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Frisio-Hoil., in 1667 by Verbiest, and finally in 1757 in Leuven), a record of a journey in Belgium and the Rhineland made in 1575.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] In 1589 he published Maris Pacifici, the first dedicated map of the Pacific to be printed.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Among his last works were an edition of Caesar (*C.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Caesaris omnia quae extant*, Leiden, Raphelingen, 1593), and the *Aurei saeculi imago, sive Germanorum veterum vita, mores, ritus et religio.* (Philippe Galle, Antwerp, 1596).
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] He also aided Welser in his edition of the Peutinger Table in 1598.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Contrary to popular belief, Ortelius, who had no children, never lived at the *Mercator-Orteliushuis* (Kloosterstraat 11–17, Antwerpen), but lived at his sister's house (Kloosterstraat 33–35, Antwerpen).
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Originals of Ortelius's maps are popular collector's items and often sell for tens of thousands of dollars.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Facsimiles of his maps are also available from many retailers.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] A map he made of North and South America is also included in the world's largest commercially available jigsaw puzzle, which is of four world maps.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] This puzzle is made by Ravensburger, measures 6 feet (1.8 m) × 9 feet (2.7 m), and has over 18,000 pieces.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Ortelius was the first to underline the geometrical similarity between the coasts of America and Europe-Africa and to propose continental drift as an explanation.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Ortelius's proposal, from his observations by visual juxtaposition, of ancient continental proximity, rupture, and separation went unnoticed until the late 20th century.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] However, they were repeated in the 18th and 19th centuries (for example, Antonio Snider-Pellegrini) and later by Alfred Wegener, who published his hypothesis of continental drift in 1912 and in following years.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Because his publications were widely available in German and English and because he adduced geological support for the idea, Wegener is credited by most geologists as the first to recognize the possibility of continental drift.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Frank Bursley Taylor (in 1908) was also an early advocate of continental drift.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] During the 1960s, geophysical and geological evidence for seafloor spreading at mid-oceanic ridges became increasingly compelling to geologists (e.g.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Hess, 1960) and finally established continental drift as an ongoing global mechanism (e.g. by the work of W.
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] Jason Morgan by 1967 and Dan McKenzie in 1968).
[src:avalites/abraham-ortelius] After more than three centuries, Ortelius's supposition of continental drift was vindicated.
[src:avalites/avalites] According to the Periplus, Avalites was part of the so-called “far-side” ports of the Barbar (the ancient Somali people), located near the Bab el-Mandeb Strait.
[src:avalites/avalites] It was the first Emporium and port of the Barbar, with the rest extending to as far as to Opone in the east.
[src:avalites/avalites] Avalites was an important center of commerce along the spice and incense trade routes.
[src:avalites/avalites] It was known for supplying and exporting ivory, tortoiseshell, and myrrh, the latter described as being of particularly high quality.
[src:avalites/avalites] Due to its proximity to the Arabian Peninsula, it was accessible by small boats and rafts, and goods were exported by local Barbar seafarers and merchants across the strait to the South Arabian ports of Ocelis and Muza under the Himyarites in todays Yemen.
[src:avalites/avalites] In return, the Barbar imported luxury items from distant lands such as Roman Egypt, particularly from Diospolis (Thebes), including textiles, as well as agricultural products such as wheat, along with wine and tin.
[src:avalites/avalites] Its inhabitants are described in the Periplus as unruly, reflecting their defensive attitude toward foreigners.
[src:avalites/avalites] Avalites’ position at the entrance to the Indo-Roman trade network, linking Roman Egypt, Arabia, and the Horn of Africa, made it a significant trading port for the Barbar people.
[src:avalites/avalites] The first mention of Avalites (or Avalita) dates to the 1st century AD, in the *Periplus of the Erythraean Sea*.
[src:avalites/avalites] Pliny, in his *Natural History*, mentioned Avalites under the names Abalitês/abalito or Abalita (Ancient Greek: Ἀβαλίτης), which is considered to be the same as the earlier Avalites/Avalita of the *Periplus*.
[src:avalites/avalites] He also mentioned the Bay of Abalitos, which is likewise considered the same as the Gulf of Avalites described in the Periplus.
[src:avalites/avalites] Ptolemy, in his 2nd-century *Geography* gives the Avalites market place at 74°00′ longitude and 8°25′ latitude, and also mentions Avalites Bay, which extends from Avalites to Aromata.
[src:avalites/avalites] Marcian of Heraclea, in his 3rd-century Periplus of the Outer Sea, references the Avalitae people and the Avalitic Gulf.
[src:avalites/avalites] He places the Gulf of Avalita on the right-hand side of the Erythraean Sea, along which the Avalitae dwell.
[src:avalites/avalites] The Avalitic Gulf has been suggested to correspond to the bay of Zeila at the head of the Gulf of Aden, although some scholars propose it refers to the Gulf of Tadjoura.
[src:avalites/avalites] Additionally, certain researchers connect the name “Avalitae” with the biblical Obal and with Ubulu mentioned in Assyrian inscriptions.
[src:avalites/avalites] The 6th-century Ethnica of Stephanus of Byzantium situates Avalites Bay in the same location as Marcian and also mentions its inhabitants.
[src:avalites/avalites] During the reign of Pharaoh Thutmose III, various settlements in the Land of Punt were recorded.
[src:avalites/avalites] At the Temple of Karnak, lists devoted to Punt contain forty names, among which is Auhar/Auhal.
[src:avalites/avalites] According to the French Egyptologist Auguste Mariette, this corresponds to what later Greco-Roman writers referred to as the Avalites emporium.
[src:avalites/avalites] Thus, the roots of Avalites extend back to the Bronze Age and it might have been a millennia old emporium at the time of the Periplus.
[src:avalites/avalites] However, the rise of the Avalite and its re-establishment took place at the end of the 1st century BCE.
[src:avalites/avalites] The Avalitae were both an ethnos and a region, from which the nearby gulf or bay derived its name, and where the port of Avalites was located.
[src:avalites/avalites] They were among the prominent inhabitants of Barbaria (northern Somalia), alongside the Mossyli of Mosylon.W.
[src:avalites/avalites] Desborough Cooley identified the Avaliae with branch of the Isaaq clan, from which one of the sub-clans of the Isaaq bears its name as Habr Awal.
[src:avalites/avalites] Some have connected the Avalitae to be the descendants of the biblical Obal, a son of Joktan (forefather of the Qahtanite).
[src:avalites/avalites] Burton links the Habr Awal people with the ancient Avalitae mentioned by Ptolemy and in the *Periplus of the Erythraean Sea*.
[src:avalites/avalites] Avalites was the principal seaport and market town/place of ancient Ethiopia, alongside Adulis and Mosylon.
[src:avalites/avalites] The local Barbar seafarers and merchants exploited their natural resources, which they exported by themselves, navigating along the Red Sea Yemenite coast (Ocelis and Muza, in the area of Al Mokha today).
[src:avalites/avalites] There might have been attempts to annex Avalites; however, due to the continuous resistance of the ancient Somalis, neighboring rulers’ ambitions failed, and foreign navigators’ and merchants’ opinions focused on the Avalites’ Berbers’ unruliness.
[src:avalites/avalites] This situation is further explained by the economic interests of the surrounding powers.
[src:avalites/avalites] The kingdom of Axum likely made the greatest efforts to subdue Avalites, not simply because of proximity, but because its income depended largely on the port of Adulis, as it controlled relatively few harbors.
[src:avalites/avalites] In contrast, the Yemenite kingdoms of Saba and Himyar already controlled extensive Red Sea coastlines and territories beyond Aden, including Azania as far as Rhapta, meaning that controlling Avalites would not have significantly increased their revenue.
[src:avalites/avalites] The trading practices of the Avalites’ Berbers are also revealing, as they preferred to export their goods through Muza and Ocelis rather than through Adulis, likely to avoid taxation and retain greater profits.
[src:avalites/avalites] By doing so, they were directly involved in major trade centers connecting Roman Egypt and India.
[src:avalites/avalites] Their exports, which included spices, small amounts of ivory, tortoise-shell, and high-quality myrrh, highlight the economic importance of Avalites, with spices and myrrh being particularly valuable commodities, while ivory and tortoise-shell were more widely available elsewhere.
[src:avalites/avalites] Zeila is considered to be the probable location of ancient avalites.
[src:avalites/avalites] The monumental *An Universal History, from the Earliest Account of Time*, identifies Zeila with the Avalita/Avarita of Ptolemy and refers to the former glory of the port, which still retains some of its ancient splendor.
[src:avalites/avalites] There has been a debate among scholars about the probable location of Avalites.
[src:avalites/avalites] Recent scholars have placed it not at Zeila but at Assab in today’s Eritrea nearby Obock in Djibouti.
[src:avalites/avalites] This identification is supported primarily by two reasons: first, the distance mentioned in the text regarding Avalites, and second, the reference to Avalites as the narrowest point of the Red Sea to Yemen.
[src:avalites/avalites] However, the ancient Somalis dominated Avalites and were its inhabitants, not the Abyssinians.
[src:avalites/avalites] The local population is described as Barbar/Berber, and the author notes that "there are other Berber market-towns" along the coast, extending further beyond Avalites towards Opone.
[src:avalites/avalites] Avalites was also the first of these Berber ports along the northern Somali coast.
[src:avalites/avalites] The Berbers lived at the edge of the Axumite kingdom, which controlled the area north of Avalites up to Adulis.
[src:avalites/avalites] Historical sources also link Avalites to the biblical land of Havilah.
[src:avalites/avalites] Saadia Gaon’s tenth-century Arabic translation of the Hebrew Bible identifies Havilah with Zeila, while some scholars consider the name Avalites itself as a demonym for Havilah.
[src:avalites/avalites] Gesenius suggested that Avalites was a city belonging to the descendants of Cush.
[src:avalites/avalites] The twelfth-century traveler Benjamin Tudela likewise described the Zeila region as the land of Havilah.
[src:avalites/avalites] Although the precise location of Havilah remains debated, it is variously placed southwest of the Arabian Peninsula or in northern Somalia.
